In the article, "When Charities Need help", Ellen Wurtner discusses how charitable has different reasonings behind donating and how philanthropists can inspire to increase charity with different approaches. There are many ways to give back in charity, such in religious institutions that are seen to be more of moral reasons driving this behavior. While they may help more to temporary needs, other might argue how charities can build more commitment to help other problem happening around world. Besides how one might give charity, it is also how charity is exposed to people, and how they respond such as using authority or drop boxes. Additionally, decision making is an important aspect to allow people choose what they want to truly donate to. Its important for others who can donate, can do it in a manner that works best for them

In 1933, President Roosevelt, had motives to develop federal public lands and use unemployed men to be able to work in project. The president made an agency called the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), and was able to enlist men 17 to 27 to help with the projects. The men who volunteered, were paid monthly, provided food, and housing. Moreover, men could only serve nine months to allows others to have an opportunity to join as well. This program made great progress in being able to work on natural forests, telephone lines, trees, roads, and more. Not only did this benefit the country, but also the men working as they were able to work, obtain diplomas, and learn more.

Planetary nebulas are an expanded form of gas cloud that later on go down in size. When more smaller, the show the core in middle which turn into a white dwarf and last billions of years in space. Before they become white dwarfs, they have a lot heat in them which correlates with a theory of stellar evolutions. It is believed before turning into a white dwarf, the heat can make a big star  create nuclear fusion. This has been seen with FG Sagittate, the heat changes during the years seen going through nuclear fusion despite temperature being low.

Many birds migrate throughout the year to adapt to seasonal changes and find a area that can accommodate this. There are many reasons around how birds can choose when to fly such as biology, nutrition, and social pressure.It is important for birds to have fuel and food availability before and after they migrate. With this birds,  must prepare before migration, but scientists found some birds, who didn't seem fit, still flew. This showed that social pressure overrides more with being healthy. As some birds start to mirgrate, other will follow too, even though they might be fueled good.

With this birds,  must prepare before migration, but scientists found some birds, who didn't seem fit, still flew. This showed that social pressure overrides more with being healthy. As some birds start to mirgrate, other will follow too, even though they might be fueled good.

Sunlike stars die stop generating energy. after that they become red and paint with a glow that increases its diameter. After that phase comes to end the star beginnings to loose its outer layers and releasing a gas. This gas is called planetary nebula and over 100,000 years the center becomes a white dwarf which will eventually fade to black or into a giant star generating a nuclear fusion. This summarizes the evolution of a star.

Reggaeton became very propular after mainstream U.S radio with daddy Yankee 2004 crossover hit = "Gasoline". It was music that was a blend of Jamaican, Latin American sals and meringue, North American hip hop and electronic music. It was thought to be orginatied from Panama although the cultivation and popularity took place in Puerto Rico. This inspired blend of Spanish rap music and dancehall reggae coming out of panama in 1970s and 80s was a perfected genre of regaeton during the early 1990's. The evolution of this type of music was the effect of underlying ethnic migrations. Jamaica labored migrated to Panama to do condtuton and they became exposed to the ragae it was solidified with the release go 1991 single becoming influential.

Observeros have noticed that birds migrant during certain temperatures. Mirgrations is a part of an annual cycle for over 50 billion birds worldwide but not all birds. Migrating can be influenced by many factors which could be more complex. The biggest factor of seasonal bird migration is timing on its weather. As temperatures get cooler birds migrant to warmer climates. Weather patterns can be unpredictable so it is clear that birds rely in an internal clock to time there seasonal movements. Migratory restlessness in caged birds they are wild embers of their species and they set off on seasonal migrations.

The book is essentially about bird migration being influenced by factors, like weather conditions. Biologists have observed that weather is a timing pressure and as cooler temperatures increase birds move towards warmer weather. It is also unpredictable to pattern seasonal weather, so bird have to rely on internal clocks to migrate. Birds need fuel to migrate, so they need sufficient food supply to navigate and form body fat which took days or weeks to complete. This is known as Russian ornithologists Viktor Dolnik and Tatiana Blyumental (1967) collected chaffinches from migrated birds along the Blatic Coast. To examine the fat content and gut food from different stages of migration to compare. They discovered only fat birds flew on the first day of migration and left at sunrise where the weather was ideal and did not feed before starting their flight but relying on stored fat for energy.

This passage is talking about how a dying star is flaring back to life. The star is FG Sagittae in the constellation where is resides at the heart of a planetary nebula known as He 1-5. For the last 30 years the star temperature has dropped, and its brightness has changed from year to year. In order, to restart the nuclear fusion of the star, astronomer need to examine the star's surface and radiation through infrared light. A research team by Robert A from the University of Minnesota has been monitoring the infrared items with three infrared photometers telescopes in Minnesota, Arizona, and Wyoming. Where they concluded that the FG Sagittae star has a strong wing peppered with carbon dust, that has been glowing. The FG Sagittae can wind thousands of Earth mass worth of carbon rich matter that can form basically life, or of a new and distant Earth.

The passage is about the new program called Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) created by President Roosevelt. The CCC program open in April 5, 1933 where many US citizen enroll to work in the National Park and Forests. They built towers, planted telephone line, roads, trials, and much more. This opportunity open the doors for many individuals and veterans out of hopelessness and provided them with outdoors, clothed, feed and taken care of better than ever in years. The program also taught them to read, write, obtain eight grade and high school diplomas.

Reggaeton began from Jamaican reggae mixing with Latin and Caribbean music in Panama and Puerto Rico, growing popular through cultural exchange as well as the famous "Dem Bow" rhythm. Reggaeton's beat comes from the "Dem Bow" rhythm, using strong drums and syncopation. Critics doubt it, but artists say its bold, urban style and Latinx makes it powerful. Reggaeton spread across U.S. cities with Puerto Rican communities and later worldwide. Despite criticism for being too repetitive or bold, it became a globally recognized and influential music genre.

A dying star becomes a red giant, then a white dwarf. Sometimes its core heats up again, briefly restarting fusion and shining like a star once more. The brief return of fusion in some dying stars fades quickly, leaving the core to cool. Scientists study changes in brightness and heat to understand these stellar events. A research team found a star, FG Sagittae, that briefly reignites nuclear fusion. Its changing brightness helps scientists study dying stars and predict how they evolve.

Bird migration is driven by weather, food, and survival needs. Changing seasons push birds to travel long distances, and scientists study how instinct and memory guide the journey. Migration also depends on food supply and daylight changes. Scientists found birds rely on stored energy, instincts, and seasonal cues to decide when and where to migrate. Different birds migrate at different times based on daylight, weather, and food. Some travel short distances, others thousands of miles, following routes shaped by their needs and habitats.

The author argues that flashy charity events often waste money and hide true needs. Real philanthropy should focus on helping people directly, not on image or publicity. Some charities now use business-style methods to attract donors and measure impact. Supporters believe that mixing profit ideas and charity can create stronger, more effective solutions worldwide. Modern charities try to teach skills and support long-term solutions. These flexible methods help groups adjust to community needs, learn from their mistakes, and improve how to help others.

Roosevelt created the civilian conservation corps to give young men jobs during the great depression. They earned small wages while helping build parks, forests, and public projects nationwide. The CCC enrolled thousands of young men in camps nationwide, giving them food, shelter, and work. Their wages were partly sent home to support their families. The CCC grew larger and completed many different projects, from fighting forest fires to building parks. The program helped young men gain skills, discipline, and hope during hard times.

The core of what is left over is usually called the white dwarf. Sometimes the core can even flicker back into a stellar life as a giant star. It is something that wont last as long as they usually will.

When this happens there is usually a thick smoke , which absorbs the star's radiation and that is because this will make it easy for to e seen.

They talk about the one of the New Deal's program that came from president Roosevelt. He cared about nature to the pont he wanted to put a program that helped that, This program is Known as The Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC). This was only supposed to last for 2 years and congress chonse not to hadle the details itself. They decided to let the president do what he thought was best for everyone while they were doing this. The War Department was the ones to give them housing and food for their nonworking hours and the Department of Agriculture and Interior were the one to design an supervise them during their projects. They would get a monthly payment of $30 or $23 to $25 of it be sent tot heir families. The estimated cost for the first year was $500 million. They were very strict on who they were accepting to work with them and they had to have specific details on how they looked within hight and weight. Some of the early enrollees were veterans who had returned to Washington, they were demanding payment of their bonuses . They were not granted on it, but they were still accepted to stay in those grounds to do what they had to do. The only way that they would be accepted by it is if they also worked with the CCC and they would get their age restiction wieved and things like that. The size of CCC raised from 350,000 to 500,000 and kept going for 7 Years. They had many achevement in these forest and parks. They had done more than a 1 thousand things during those 7 years. They helped many young men who had nothing and they helped them become something. When they were done there these men belived in something and belived in them selves.

This talks about how Reggaeton started and from what types of genres it came from. It is a type of migration that it did through places. It was said that it came from Panama, But was made recognized even more because of many other artist, many who are from Puerto RicoIt was seen that It was mostly started because of a song called "Dem Bow". They talk about the beats that it has and how it is similar to the beats of another two genres. Reggaeton became such a genre with such a stable defining characteristic. Many times Reggaeton can somewhat be repetative because of the destict beats it has. Puerto Rican DJ Playero helped introduce communities with reggaeton in the 1990s. He started with communities of with a lot of Puerto Rican in them. From there It started evolving to many other places. Even with much feedback because of lyrics or type of music it has become such a big thing that it has become a global prevalence in the early part of this century.

Reggaeton music has a long history making it's grand entrance with Daddy Yankee's "Gasolina." It was thought to have been originated in Panama, but the cultivation and popularity of its signature style took place in Puerto Rico. The evolution of reggaeton is the effect of underlying ethnic migration and the resulting of cultural overlaps. The song "Dem Bow" can be pinpointed as the catalyst for a new genre as it is the underlying rhythm to almost every reggaeton song. Reggaeton's popularity has extended internationally.

By producing carbon dust that blocks its light, FG sagittae is making a rare appearance, requiring astronomers to use more sophisticated equipment. Carbon dust emissions could lead to the emergence of new planets. It would be a waste of material for future worlds if it turned into a white dwarf.

Although reggaeton was already well liked un Latin America, it didn't become popular in the United Sates until 2004. It originated in Panama and gained popularity in Puerto Rico. This is basically a blend of Hip hop, Latin music, and Jamaican reggae. The "Dem Bow" rhythm eventually evolved into the fundamental beats of reggaeton. Artists claims that this is the pint to strengthen the genre's individuality, while some claim it is overly repetitious. Latino kids find the genre appealing because it feels independent, bold, contemporary, and familiar to their culture.

Birds migrate to breeding grounds and wintering destinations. Due to its unpredictability, migratory timing is not solely determined by the weather. Instead, birds have a built in clock. A bird's food source is crucial to their ability to procreate. A 1967 study on chaffinches revealed that larger, healthier birds migrate first in pleasant weather, while smaller birds migrate in bad weather because of social pressure. However, other birds, such as wandering albatrosses, rely on their unique wings for currents and low-energy movements while migrating over great distances.

Roosevelt created the Civilian Corps to assist men without jobs and the environment. These workers were employed to work on conservation projects in parks, national forests, and public areas. These men gave their families their $30 they made each month. Before it ended in 1942 the CCC had almost 3 million troops, demonstrating the quick growth. The workers planted trees, constructed roads, pathways, fire towers, and general flood control. Eleanor Roosevelt assisted Bonus Army Veterans in enlisting. In addition to providing basic necessities, housing, and education for young men this organization benefited the environment.

Birds migrate seasonally, usually moving to warmer areas when the weather gets colder and returning to cooler breeding grounds in spring and summer. Not all birds migrate, but billions do each year. Weather influences when birds begin migrating, but it is unpredictable. Because of this, birds also rely on an internal biological clock, shown by the migratory restlessness biologists see even in caged birds.

When a sun-like star is about to die, it first becomes a red giant, then it blows off its outer layers and forms a planetary nebula. Whats left in the center becomes a white dwarf, which slowly cools and fades over billions of years. However, sometimes the cores temperature suddenly rises again. When that happens, the star can briefly flare back to life and start producing energy one more time through nuclear fusion.

Charitable giving used to be mostly driven by religious groups, focusing on helping people with basic needs like food and shelter. While this is kind and moral, some experts think it doesnt fix deeper problems. Today, charities are becoming more business-like, using branding and creative ways to help, like clothing drop boxes. This new approach aims to make giving more effective and long-lasting.

President Roosevelt cared deeply about people and the environment, including trees. He even enlisted young unemployed men to work on the national forests, parks, and other federal public lands. The program is called the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC). Congress authorized it, and it was to last two years. The men were to be paid $30 a month, with anywhere from $23 to $25 of it to be sent to their families.

When people think of charitable giving, they often envision dropping change into a basket at church or into the hands of someone experiencing homelessness. But is there a better way? Ted Stumbacher, head of the Global Empowerment Initiative, believes that to achieve effective philanthropy, it must have at its core a more economic mindset. He believes that religious organizations often provide only a temporary solution. Nonprofits are finding non-monetary solutions, like clothing recycling.

Before a sunlike star "dies" or stops creating energy through nuclear fusion, it becomes a red giant growing to a hundred times its original size. The star sheds its outer layers, giving rise to an expanding gas cloud known as a planetary nebula. Then, it swells in size and drops in density for at most another 100,00 years, exposing the remaining stellar core at its center. That core becomes a white dwarf, the most common celestial cadaver visible in the sky. It radiates its leftover heat into space for billions of years, and slowly fades to black.

Bird species make seasonal trips between cooler breeding grounds in the spring and summer, and warmer locations in autumn and winter. Migration is a part of the annual cycle of over 50 billion individual birds worldwide. Not all birds migrate. There are many species, particularly in the tropics, that remain in a single residence throughout the year. But the biological mechanisms that prompt birds to choose a particular date to begin migration are more complex and appear to be influenced by many factors. 

The most obvious factor is the weather. However, seasonal weather patterns are known to be unpredictable. Therefore, it is clear that birds must rely more on an internal clock to time their seasonal movements.

Reggaeton made its entrance onto mainstream U.S. radio with Daddy Yankee's 2004 crossover hit, "Gasolina". It is thought to have originated in Panama, although the cultivation and popularity of its signature style took place in Puerto Rico. The evolution of reggaeton can be understood as the effect of underlying ethnic migration and the resulting cultural overlaps. The reggae genre was solidified with the release of a 1991 single by Jamaican dancehall star Shabba Ranks, "Dem Bow".

This article describes the cycle of a sunlike star before it essentially "dies". The very last phase is when the core becomes a white dwarf, and it ends up radiating its' leftover heat into space for billions years and will eventually fade to black. But for some white dwarfs they don't follow that same routine of slowly fading away, instead the core can fluctuate in temperature like crazy, and temporarily flick into a giant star. Though these white dwarfs aren't very long lived, because the core doesn't have enough fuel. They use the star FG Sagittae as a perfect example, this star has fluctuated in temperature dramatically in the past thirty years, and as it tries to restart nuclear fusion it releases a think carbon atom filled puff of smoke. Researchers have now found that the same puff of carbon atoms can potentially be means for life.

They use the star FG Sagittae as a perfect example, this star has fluctuated in temperature dramatically in the past thirty years, and as it tries to restart nuclear fusion it releases a think carbon atom filled puff of smoke. Researchers have now found that the same puff of carbon atoms can potentially be means for life.

This article talks about how present FDR changed the lives of many with his new proposal for a program young men and veterans. This program called the Civilian Conservation Corps, the program was originally imagined to be a volunteer "army"  when young men could enlist and be put to work, specifically in national forest, national parks and other federal public lands. The men were paid monthly but majority of their income went to their families, this was because the men had a place to live eat and shower. Though just not any man would join they had specific weight and height requirements and could only join if they were in between the ages of 17 and 24. Through this program, many learned to read and write and received eighth grade and high school diplomas. By the time the program ended in 1942, the men had built 3.470 fire towers, 65,000 miles of telephone lines were installed,  fire breaks were scraped and grounded and 97,000 of miles of track rails and road were bult.

This article emphasizes our need to recognize reggaeton and the genre that it is. It briefly describes the history, and and evolution of reggaeton mentioning how many artist first took the inspiration from many Jamaican tunes. One of the first pioneers in reggaeton was El General and his first song "dem bow" seems to be key tune in many other reggaeton songs. Reggaeton is a genre of music that has a little of everything provocative lyrics, good beat, a story. Many like to discredit the genre because every song sounds like the one before, but we shouldn't over look the uniqueness and street creditabilty of it.

This article talks about the influential factors of the yearly cycle of migration for over 50 million birds. One of the most obvious factors is weather, birds in temperate climate areas move in the direction of warmer areas. Due to weather unpredictability, birds have to rely on their internal clock  when it comes to migration. Food is another big factor that determines the movement if birds when resources are too scarce, many species anticipate this change and adjust their migrating schedule accordingly .

The passage explains that charity has usually meant small, religion-driven donations that give short-term help, like food or shelter. Ted Stumbacher argues that this traditional model doesnt fix the deeper causes of poverty. He says newer charities act more like businesses, using marketing, branding, and things like clothing drop boxes to reach more people and make help more sustainable.

Most migratory birds move mainly because food supplies change with the seasons, and they need plenty of nutrition and stored fat both to reproduce and to fuel long flights. The 1967 chaffinch study showed that the fattest, healthiest birds migrate first under good conditions, and their early departure creates social pressure that pushes thinner, less-prepared birds to follow, even in bad weather. The passage also explains that some species, like wandering albatrosses, migrate vast distances with relatively low energy cost by using specialized wings and wind patterns, spending much of their lives in the air traveling between distant habitats.

The 1967 chaffinch study showed that the fattest, healthiest birds migrate first under good conditions, and their early departure creates social pressure that pushes thinner, less-prepared birds to follow, even in bad weather. Over two decades, astronomers tracked FG Sagittae in infrared light and found that, although its surface has cooled, it is still shining very brightly because intense stellar winds are blowing huge amounts of carbon-rich dust into space. These winds will eventually stop when fusion finally ends, but by then the star will have ejected many Earth-masses of material that could seed new planets and perhaps even future life in distant star systems.

The passage describes how President Franklin Roosevelt, drawing on his interest in forestry, created the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) to put unemployed young men to work on conservation projects in national forests, parks, and other public lands during the Great Depression. It explains that responsibility for the program was divided among several federal departments, that the men earned small wages (most of which were sent home), and that the CCC quickly grew into a massive program that built firebreaks, roads, trails, campgrounds, bridges, floodcontrol works, and planted billions of trees while improving wildlife refuges. Finally, it emphasizes that the CCC not only transformed the American landscape but also changed the lives of its enrollees by taking them out of urban poverty, giving them food, shelter, education, discipline, and selfesteem, and even drawing in World War I veterans who accepted Roosevelts offer of steady work and joined the camps.

~1 billion yrs ago -> sunlike star "dies." It then becomes a red giant, and grows 100 hundred times its diameter. Next, the red-giant phase ends and the star blows off its outer laters. It then becomes a planetary nebula which increases in size and drops in density. This exposes its core, which then becomes a white dwarf, that radiates its leftover heat into space.

- many bird species make seasonal trips from cooler --> to warmer locations in the fall/winter. Migration is the annual cycle of many birds in the world. However, seasonal weather patterns are unpredictable which leads us to believe it's more of an internal clock.

- 1993 President Roosevelt brought 2 concerns together: enlisting young unemployed men in a volunteer "army" to work in national parks/national forests. He called it the "Civilian Corps Reforestation Youth Rehabilitation Movement." It was then changed to the "Civilian Conservation Corps" (CCC). Congress authorized the president to create the program & structure it as he saw fit. Responsibilities were split up among the Labor Department. The men were paid 30 dollars a month, and anywhere from 23 to 25 dollars were sent to their families.

-Reggaeton music made its entrance into mainstream U.S. radio with Daddy Yankee's hit 'Gasolina' in 2004. By that time, reggaeton had been well established and widespread throughout Latin American countries. It has been thought that it originated in Panama,  although the popularity of its signature style took place in Puerto Rico. Puerto Ricans perfected the genre of reggaeton during the early '90s. The evolution of reggaeton can be understood as the effect of ethnic migrations & cultural overlaps. In the first half of the 20th century, Jamaican laborers migrated to Panama to assist with the construction of the Panama Canal. Panamanians became exposed to the Jamaican reggae. In the second half of the 20th century, the Jamaican reggae was infiltrating Puerto Rico. The reggaeton was solidified with the release of "Dem Bow" by Shabba Ranks. It was then recorded in Spanish by El General as "Son Bow."

The article summarizes the modern history of reggaeton. The first half explores the modern origins of the genre and how it came from Jamaicans that worked on the Panama Canal, their music as adapted for Panamanians and how in the 20th century reggaeton was blende with Puerto Rico into the version we know today. When people described reggaeton there are two views; some struggle to take the genre seriously while other explain that the music is meant to be more underground. Even with the popularity it's still struggles to be taken seriously.

To summarize, FDR created a program that would allow young man that had no job to work in national parks where food, clothes and shelter would be provided for them. The program first acronym was CCRYRM and later shortened to CCC. The program would pay $30 a month, and $23- $25 would be sent to families. The program first started on April 5, 1933, with 250,000 housed in 1,468 camps around the country. By the time the program was cut the young man had built; 3,470 fire towers, 650,100 miles of telephone lines, hauled diseased trees, planted 1.3 billion new ones, and made roads, campgrounds, bridges, recreation and administrative facilities. This program also greatly benefited the man as they were not only fed, clothed and house but many learned how to read and write, got both 8th grade and high school diplomas as well as a boost of self-esteem.

To summarize birds' migration is complex and scientists are trying to figure out why these birds migrate at different times of the year. One conclusion they came to is the weather as many birds typically migrate to warmer climate due to the shifting seasons, yet they aren't so sure as the climate in unpredictable and with also seeing captured birds having a phenomenon called "migratory restlessness" it can be assumed that most birds have an interval clock that tells them when to migrate. Another possible explanation they came up with is the food supply being a big factor as Russian ornithologist Viktor Dolnik and Tatiana Blyumental watched birds migrate in different waves, they noted that the ones that had more fat were the ones that migrated first as well as they did not eat and relied on the fat stored. They still watched the waves as more and more of the leaner birds started to migrate; some which were still eating and others that eat before leaving even when the weather would have made it hard for them to migrate. Although these findings don't take into account other birds (sea birds, raptors, or natural species) or how long their migration last, they help paint a few factors as to way some birds may migrate.

To summarize the articles, talk about how when a sun-like start dies a white dwarf is left behind that slowly burns out until it's gone. However, some researchers have noticed that these white dwarfs have sometimes started to show light again like they used to but often times it doesn't last. An example of one of these white dwarfs is the star, FG Sagittae. This "dead" star has been shown to sometimes flare up like it's coming back to live before dying out again. A professor leads a research team to look into this star which includes having three telescopes: one in Arizona, one in Minnesota and another in Wyoming. The information gathered shows that although FG has flared up the core is still way to cool for it to start nuclear fusion again.

The reggaeton music entered the U.S. mainstream radio with Daddy Yanke's 2004 hit "Gasolina", but the genre had a long thrieved in Latin America. It originated in Panama but was perfected and became popular in Puerto Rico. Reggaetin blends dancehall reggae, salsa, merengue, hip-hop, and electronic music. its evolution reflects cultural mixing, especially Jaimaican migration to Panama. Shabba Ranks's 1991 song "Dem Bow", later adapted by El General, became the rhythmic foundation of nearly all reggaeton. Critics call it repetitive, but artist argue this strengthens its underground appeal. Its bold electronic sound and urban lyrics attract youth, helping reggaeton spread globally despite complains about violence and suggestive content.

The Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), created by FDR in 1933, employed young, unemployed men to wokr on national forest, parks, and public lands. The participants received various benefits like pay, housing, and education while performing projects like reforestation, fire control, and infrastructure building. The program was expanded over the years aiding veterans and teaching skills, discipline, and literacy. A sunlike star dies, it expands into a red giant, sheds its outer layers, and become a white dwarf. Some stars, like FG Sagittae, briefly reignite nuclear fusion, creating flares and carbon-rich stellar winds. Astronomers studying its infrared emissions found steady carbon dust, which may seed interstellar dust and future planetary formation. After this short stellar revival, the star will return to white dwarfhood, leaving lasting cosmic effects.

Many birds migrate seasonally between breeding and wintering grounds, guided by weahter, food available, and internal biological clocks. Observations of "migratory restlessness" and studies on chaffinches suggest social pressure and physical conditions influence migration timing. While most migrants travel moderate distances, some, like wandering albotrosses, cover thounsands of kilimeters using specialized wings and air currents. migrations strategies vary across species, reflecting adaptations to energy needs, environmental conditions, and social influences.

Traditional charity often provides temporary relief, ussually through religious institutions. Modern philanthropy, however, emphasizes long-term impact, donor choice, and innovative approaches. Organizations like Donors Choose, Taste of Giving, and the Acumen Fund use marketing, events, and microloans to address systematic issues, engaged donors, and maximize effectiveness. While scaling these methods poses challenges, such strategies broaden donor participation, inspire established charities to improve, and promotes sustainable solutions to poverty and social needs.

A "sunlike star" will grow largely in size and appear a red color billions of years before dying. Subjected to different phases, it will result in a planetary nebula which is a cloud of gas. Following the same process, this nebula will grow have a lower density for thousands of ears. What is left is the core, also known as the white dwarf. This dwarf will go from radiating heat to slowly fading away. 
There is a star called the FG Sagittae that has made efforts to revive in a way. It will continue to shine somewhat steadily and a temperature that is rather low for a few more hundred years. Ultimately it will revert to being a white dwarf again after its carbon dust "blanket" has dispersed. In the end what will be left range from asteroids, moons, etc.

President Roosevelt solved both the concern of jobs and preservation of nature with his Civilian Corps Reforestation out Rehabilitation Movement, later known as the Civilian Conservation Corps. the Labor Department was tasked in employing young men to work in national forests/parks/etc. These young men would be housed and fed. Above all they would be compensated for their work, around $30 a month. 
There were quite a few restrictions on the type of men that could work. Decided by age, capability of physical labor, height, weight, even teeth. Nonetheless, around 250,000 men were enrolled in the first year, for no more than nine-months. 
As the years passed, enrollment would reach 500,000 and held strong until 1942. In the end, more than three million jobs were provided, resulting in countless fire towers, telephone lines, fire breaks, roads, trails, truck trails, roads, etc. 
The CCC left a positive impact of many American's. Providing them with meaningful work, food, and shelter.

President Roosevelt solved both the concern of jobs and preservation of nature with his Civilian Corps Reforestation out Rehabilitation Movement, later known as the Civilian Conservation Corps. the Labor Department was tasked in employing young men to work in national forests/parks/etc. These young men would be housed and fed. Above all they would be compensated for their work, around $30 a month. 
There were quite a few restrictions on the type of men that could work. Decided by age, capability of physical labor, height, weight, even teeth. Nonetheless, around 250,000 men were enrolled in the first year, for no more than nine-months. 
As the years passed, enrollment would reach 500,000 and held strong until 1942. In the end, more than three million jobs were provided, resulting in countless fire towers, telephone lines, fire breaks, roads, trails, truck trails, roads, etc. 
The CCC left a positive impact of many American's. Providing them with meaningful work, food, and shelter.

Reggaeton is derived from a blend of Jamaican reggae, Latin salsa, and American hip-hop. Originated in Panama, but really thriving in Puerto Rico, Reggaeton was a true hybrid of many music cultures. Starting with Jamaican migrants to Panama, Panamanians were exposed to Jamaican dancehall reggae. Officially recognized as its own genre with Panamanian El General's Spanish song "Son Bow" which was a cover of "Dem Bow" by Jamaican Shabba Banks. 
Reggaeton is an underground style that is a bold blend of different musics. Although easily recognizable, that does not diminish its appeal. 
Spread throughout the US mainly through Puerto Rican communicates in New York and Los Angeles. The 90s gave rise to stars like Daddy Yankee, Don Chezina and more. 
Often criticized for lacing imagination or being too repetitive, this genre is still a display of the history of many. It is deserving of recognition.

Many species of birds, particularly tropical birds, migrate between to cooler locations in the spring and summer and warmer location in the autumn and winter. But it's not that simple. This journey is influenced by many factors and the birds and intentional with their timing. Weather is one of the main tale tells, although unpredictable. Due to this the birds rely on an internal clock to decide when to migrate. There is something called the "migratory restlessness" that impacts caged birds since they are able to migrate. 
Furthermore, food also serves as a factor. Seasonal changed directly impact the abundance of food like berries, insects, etc. So birds must not only worry about when food will run out but they have to leave before it becomes scare to bulk up. This is to use their body fat as fuel during their journey to different locations. Dolnik and Blyumental, Russian ornithologists studied migrating Chaffinches on their journey along the Baltic Coast. They found that only fate birds flew on the first day of each wave of migration by studying their fat content and amount of food they had in the carcasses. Relying on their stored fat, the birds left at the best time suited for an easy flight. 
During the soon wave, once again only the fat birds flew. As time passed the lean birds also joined in, using their stored energy from that mornings breakfast. It was noted that this study can not be used for all birds since only Chaffinches were studied. Not representing sea birds, raptors, nocturnal species, etc. Furthermore many birds travel much further than the Chaffinches, travels up to hundreds of kilometers. Additionally, even sea birds are different since they rely on their specific wing structure to aid in migration.

Charitable giving goes beyond just dropping change into the Salvation Army basket or into the hands of the homeless. According to Ted Stumbacher, to really provide a more permanent relief to the unfortunate, it must start with an economic mindset. He believes that establishing a "life-long commitment" idea to philanthropy will be far more sucessful than simply just providing occasional food and clothing. From increasing attention to their marketing images to spread their consumer awareness, to having clothing-recycling drop boxes around cities, these are more beneficial in the end.
This is also said to improve the customers opinion on giving back. They are able to make decisions in how and where their money is used depending one what charitable projects they choose. Furthermore, Acumen Fund found Novogratz also finds that the start to ending poverty must be tacked with an economic mindset. This is the best way to a more tenable form of permanent aid. 
The point is to not help someone for just on day, but to set them up for success for good. Redefining charity is better for both the donors and those who are in need.

Furthermore, Acumen Fund found Novogratz also finds that the start to ending poverty must be tacked with an economic mindset. This is the best way to a more tenable form of permanent aid. 
The point is to not help someone for just on day, but to set them up for success for good. Redefining charity is better for both the donors and those who are in need.

This article describes how the CCC, or Civilian Conservation Corps came to be under the supervision of President Roosevelt. It was a cooperative effort that joined the hands of multiple departments, from Labor, Agriculture and Interior, and War. They coordinated men paid a generous 30$ a month, setting up the infrastructure necessary to manage sprawling nature preserves. This work also provided many with employment as well as a way to get out of the urban deadlock many found themselves stuck in

This article details the boom in popularity Revgaeton music experienced in the early 20th century, talking about what played into that success. It a syncretic phenomenon that arose from Jamaican reggae mixed with Spanish thanks to the influx of Jamaican migrant workers entering Panama to construct the canal. Although it seemed to result in some mainstream backlash, attracting some ridicule, others in the subculture believe it to heighten the appeal, seeing it as an underground movement. And the spread into coastal cities along the east and west coast of US into the 1990s gives credence to this

The article describes the seasonal migration of birds from cooler breeding locations in spring and summer to warmer regions in autumn and winter. They detail the reasons, from weather and food, tracked internally on a biological clock that triggers migratory restlessness in caged birds.One example they gave was that of chaffinches studied as they migrated along the Baltic Coast. They stored energy for the migration, relying on stored fat rather than feeding. They also noted other reasons for departure timings, suggesting a social aspect rather than purely good weather patterns

This article details the process charity generally uses to aid those in need - such as soup kitchens and alms for the poor. Then the transformation during modern times to spreading awareness in an almost capitalistic method via celebrity endorsement to maintain market share, emphasizing the consumer choice aspect of giving. They then argue that this is superior to the traditional approaches as it essentially teaches a man to fish, providing poor with investment opportunities. Though they point out arguments against ,which say that such an initiative is untenable on larger scales

Bires store energy as body fat before migrating and often rely on the stored fat insetad of feeding during early travel. The passage highlights how migratory patterns in birds have been a mystery for centuries. The most speculated theory is that birds migrate due to the weather patterns yet seasonal weather patterns are unpredictable. The article "Migration" inquires a new theory that looks at chaffinches as they migrate and examining physically fit birds vs unhealthy birds in migration. Russian Ornithologist theorized that migratory patterns maybe due to the physical fitness of birds and their physical consumption of food, and how social pressure in the flock affects migratory patterns.

The passage "The Ascension of Reggaeton" by Eric Delgado highlights a genre of music that recently became mainstream by Daddy Yankee's "Gasolina". Reggaeton has been said to of originated in Panama but it became popularized in Puerto Rico. This reggaeton genre was popularized in 1991 with "Dem Bow" and Dem Bow's rhythm is what makes a reggaeton song, fit into the genre of reggaeton. Reggaeton is criticized because of it's irony as stated by Ethan Perry. Eventhough Reggaeton has been criticized it continues to flourish. During 1990s and onwards in 2004 with Gasolina, many artists make the genre what it is. That energy and the genre that is reggaeton is unlike other genres.

The passage highlights the New Deal and the program called the Civilian Conservation Corps.  The CCC began in 1933. In this program, men who were U.S citizens ages seventeen and twenty-seven out of school and out of work , who were physically capable of labor were able to serve. Roosevelt made this program and it expanded quickly, in only one year the CCC rose in employment. This caused for the national forests to have fire towersm and telephone lines, additionally the planted 1.3 billion trees. This program was very important for the National Park Service as it allowed for roads to be built, campgrounds and for the Biological Survey to be formed. The CCC brought recorded level amounts of employment and is the  reason why we have so many programs that protect our National parks, as well as protect our wildlife.

This passage highlights a phenomenon called white dwarfs, which are planetary nebula that radiates leftover heat in space before fading into nothingness. This passage specifically looks at the FG Sagittae which is on a planetary nebula. Upon examination they see that smoke absorbs into the stars heat. The wavelength is measured to determine what happens in FG Sagittae. A research team found just that, they were able to interpret how hot FG sagittae is and how long it has been powering in the last decade.

President Franklin D. Roosevelt, father of the New Deal, killed two birds with one stone when it came to the issue of tree preservation and jobs, by tasking people to be part of a volunteer "army" and help establish national forests and parks. It would be known as the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC). Congress allowed the president to make the program and do what he wished. The CCC would officially begin on April 5, 1933, costing $500 million in the first year. The CCC was able to put more than 3 million people to work and built roads, bridges, etc. while also fighting fires and planting new trees. The program was a major success and stands as a testament of the greater fight to protect nature's most beautiful creations.

Reggateton music entered U.S. radios with Daddy Yankee's 2004 "Gasolina." At that time, reggaeton had already had a strong presence throughout Latin American countries. Thought to have originated from Panama, its cultivation and popularity took place in Puerto Rico. Its evolution reflects cultural overlaps and ethnic migrations around the Americas, allowing for the creation of unique and new hybrid musical forms.

Towards the end of a star's lifetime, it will become a red giant and grow to a hundred times its original size before blowing off its outer layers, creating an expanding gas cloud called a planetary nebula. The planetary nebula swells and drops in density for another 100,000 years. The core then becomes a white dwarf, radiating its leftover heat for billions of years before fading to black. Robert A. Gehrz of the University of Minnesota in Minneapolis led a research team to monitor the infrared properties of FG Sagittae with three telescopes that have infrared photometers.

Over 50 billion individual birds migrate every year as part of the annual cycle. A major factor in the timing of seasonal bird migration is the weather. When it cools and precipitates, birds will migrate to the direction of warmer weather. Even so, seasonal weather patterns are often unpredictable, meaning that birds must rely more on an internal clock to time their movements. Even for caged birds, they will become "restless" at the same time as migratory birds. Another factor in migratory patterns is food supply, which birds need to reproduce and survive during their migration.

Well regarded for the New Deal, Roosevelt initiated the "tree farmer" silviculture program. 

In 1933, he enlisted young men as volunteers to care for forests on federal lands throuh a reforestation and youth rehabilitation initiative. This program, originally known as the Civilian Corps Reforestation Youth Rehabilitation movements, later became the Civilian Conseration Corps (CCC). The President established the CCC by executive order, initially set to last two years. The Labor Deparment was tasked with selecting enrollees, while the WAr Department provided housing and food during non-working hours. The Department of Agriculture and Interior planned and supervised projects in natioinal and regional forests, parks, and other public lands.

When poeple think about charitable giving they often imagine donations to places like houses of worship, the salvation Army, or Handing money to a homeless person. The author explains that philanthropy is deeply connected to religion, morality, and generosity, often seen as a way to honor God. Religious organizations and their churches have historically helped the poor through soup kitchens and hunger relief efforts. 

Ted Stumbacher of the Global Empowerment Initiative argues that effective philanthropy should move beyond just an economic mindset. He believes religious organizations provide temp aid but don't address the bigger picture that would truly help people in need. According to him, their help mainly benefits hose who want to be generous rather than those who most need assistance. Over the past 20 years, new forms of philanthropy have emerged, focusing more on celebrating and branding the helpers instead of just the help itself. Even though these nonprofits don't aim for profit, they try to maximize their "market share" like large corps, finding new non-monetary ways to assist, such as recycling cloths that not only cloth people but also help the environment.

Even though these nonprofits don't aim for profit, they try to maximize their "market share" like large corps, finding new non-monetary ways to assist, such as recycling cloths that not only cloth people but also help the environment.

Religious organizations and their churches have historically helped the poor through soup kitchens and hunger relief efforts.

Many bird species travel seasonally moving between cooler breeding surroundings in the spring and summer and warmer regions in the fall and winter. Migration involves over 50 billion birds worldwide, though not all species migrate, esp those in tropical areas that remain in one place year 'round. 
The timing of migration is influenced by variety of factors, but as climate change manifests it becomes unreliable indicators wince weather patterns shift unpredictably. Birds also cannot always rely on visual cues like the sun/stars due to cloud cover. 
Scientists believe that birds rely on internal biological clocks to know when to migrate. The idea is supported by the observation of "migratory restlessness," a behavior shown by caged birds at the same time that wild birds of their species begin their seasonal journeys.

Reggaeton became popular in the U.S. w/Daddy Yankee's 2004 hit "Gasolina," but the genre had already been developping in Latin America. It combines Jamaican dancehall reggae, Latin rhythms like salsa and merengue, and American hip-hop. The genere likely began in Panama, where Jamican workers introduced raggae while building the Panama Canal, but Puerto Rico perfected and popularized it in the 1990's.

The musics evolution shows how migration and culturale exchange create hybrid art forms. Panamanians adapted Jamican reggae into Spanish, and later Puerto Rican DJs incorporated dancehall and electronic beats. A key moment came with Jamaican artist Shabba Ranks "Dem Bow" whose ryhtm became the foundatioin all reggaeton songs for generations to come.

Before a star like the Sun reaches the end of its life, it expands into a red giant about a hundred ties larger than its original size. As this phase ends, the star sheds its outer layer, forming a glowing gas cloud called nebula. The stars hot core, now exposed, beomes a white dwarf, which gradually cools and dims over billions of year, but some stars "flare back to life."
During this late stage, unstable temperatures in the star's core can rise dramatically, reaching high millions of degrees. These sudden bursts may briefly restart nuclear fusion, causing the fading star to shine like a diamond one last time before it ultimately cools into darkness.

During this late stage, unstable temperatures in the star's core can rise dramatically, reaching high millions of degrees. These sudden bursts may briefly restart nuclear fusion, causing the fading star to shine like a diamond one last time before it ultimately cools into darkness.

The passage discusses about the migration of birds as they migrate towards locations that are colder when in hot weather and warmer locations in cold weather, yet it's not confirmed on when birds know when to migrate. Though we can assume factors that can let them know such as precipitate increasing can indicate colder weather as the temperature drops, but the weather can be unpredictable due to climate change or by the clouds which can be confusing From this, we can assume birds rely on an internal time clock to determine when to migrate and not on outside factors.

This passage discusses about what happens after sunlike star "dies" as the star FD Sagittae had reignited nuclear fusion for a brief moment after becoming a white dwarf. It was found that the star runs on fumes that would eventually run out though when the star would briefly ignite, carbon atoms would be coughed up from the core, forming clouds and the smoke absorbs the star's heat, though it loses vast amount of material each year. When fusion stops again and the carbon atoms cool down, they can create the formation of rocks asteroids, planets and other form of life.

This passage discusses about Present Roosevelt creating the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC)in 1933 where jobs were given to young unemployed men during the Great Depression. They worked on different projects like planting trees and building roads, etc. and were paid $30 a month and majority were sent to their families. Eventually, the CCC employed more than 3 million men while improving the environment and helping civilians to get a job if they were unemployed.

Reggaeton is thought to have started in Panama, but the popularity and developments of the style took place in Puerto Rico. Puerto Ricans were inspired by the mix of Spanish rap music and dancehall reggae coming out of Panama in the 1970s and 1980s. In the first half of the 20th century, Panamanians became exposed to and captivated with Jamaican reggae, recording Spanish language versions of Jamaican reggae songs. The reggaeton genre was strengthened with the release of a single by Jamaican dancehall arist Ranks ("Dem Bow"). The beat of the song proved to be influential and referred to as "Dem Bow" became the background rhythm of almost every reggaeton song.

It has been well known that many bird species make seasonal trips between cooler breeding grounds in the spring and summer and warmer locations in the autumn and winter. However, there are many species in the tropics that maintain a single residence year round. As the weather cools and precipitation increases, birds living in temperate climates move in the direction of warmer weather. It's clear that birds rely on an internal clock to time their seasonal movements where there is migratory restlessness in caged birds at the same time the wild members of their species set off on seasonal migrations.

A planetary nebula which is an expanding gas cloud increases in size and drops in density to reveal the remaining stellar core at its center. According to the theory of stellar evolution, the temperature in the stellar core can change wildly and sometimes spikes as high as tens of millions of degrees. For a little while, the core may flicker back into stellar life as a giant star generating new energy with new flares of nuclear fusion.

For a little while, the core may flicker back into stellar life as a giant star generating new energy with new flares of nuclear fusion.

Many bird species migrate every season. There are many factors that influence birds to select a particular date to migrate. One factor is the weather. When it gets colder, birds migrate to warmer areas. However, weather patterns cannot be accurately predicted, so biologists have observed that caged birds have "migratory restlessness" at the same time as wild birds who migrate too areas based on the season.

Overall, the passage calls for a shift from temporary charity to sustainable and impactful giving.

When a star runs out of fuel it expands into a red giant and sheds its outer layers forming a nebula with a white dwarf core that slowly fades. However, some dying stars briefly flare back to life when their cores heat up again and creates new bursts of nuclear fusion before finally dimming for good.

A billion years before a sunlike star dies it will become a red giant and expand 100x its original size. Then the next 100,000 years it will become a white dwarf. The transition from white dwarf until the star stops producing energy is not always calm and the temperature of the star can change in tens of millions of degrees.

Since Daddy Yankee's Gasolina in 2004, Reggaeton has creeped into mainstream U.S radio. Its a blend of Spanish rap and dancehall reggae. Jamaicans who went to Panama introduced Jamaican reggae and Panamanians recorded Spanish-language versions of Jamaican reggae songs, which later made its way to Puerto Rico. Music critics have criticized reggaeton for being unimaginative and only having a single set of beats, but reggaeton artist Felioe says that that only boosts the reggaeton genre. Now reggaeton is being recognized universally and has made its way into Europe and Asia as well.

The CCC was created to combine the interest of saving nature and helping unemployed men.  The men had to be 17-27 years of age and U.S citizens serving no more than 9 terms so they could cycle in as many people as possible. The program reached great numbers and led to a lot of successful projects and building innovations. The overall effect on the workers as well was incredible as it gave them hope, helped them read and write and gave structure and discipline to lives that seemed like they had little self esteem and optimism.

Birds have different migration cycles throughout the seasons. Weather is a big hindrance to bird migration. Food is important for storing energy to fuel migration. Fat birds were able to fly at favorable weather conditions due to stored fat, and the leaner the bird was the later they'd migrate. Leaner birds felt pressure to migrate even if they weren't physically ready. Some migratory birds travel great distances, much more than chaffinches and have distinct characteristics in their wing structure that help combat the challenges of heavy winds.

Roosevelt established the CCC with the intention of helping the people as well as the environment and infrastructure. The president himself structured the program, assigning takss to many departments and establishing a criteria for what sort of men were allowed to partake in it. There are many criteria, but it generally leans toward an "average" picture of a young healthy male who would not be burdened by the responsibility of the program, as these men where not students or employed. Despite the strict criteria, Roosevelt allowed veterans to participate as well, seeing as they were not being provided the benefits they were promised for serving their country. 
The program was a great success, not only in terms of infrastructure development but also providing a sense of purpose and stability to many young citizens.

About a billion years before a sunlike star dies, it expands into a red giant. It's outer layers become planetary nebulae and it turns into a white dwarf, cooling for billions of years before becoming a black dwarf. Some stars reignite before the end of their life cycle. 
FG Sagittae in the constellation Sagitta appears to be one such case. It has cooled by a large degree over the recent decades while changing in brightness. During its fusion restart, it ejects carbon "smoke" that obscures its light.
Astronomers led by Robert A. Gehrz monitored FG Sagittae's infrared emissions for twenty years, finding its carbon dust glows steadily at about 1,200F. They estimate the star loses anywhere from 1.57.5 quadrillion tons of material per second through intense stellar winds.
Once this brief fusion episode ends, the dust and wind will cease, and FG Sagittae will resume its path to becoming a white dwarf. The expelled carbon may eventually contribute to interstellar dust.

Many bird species migrate seasonally between breeding and wintering grounds, guided by both environmental and biological factors. In addition to weather and food availability, birds use internal clocks to time migration, as shown by migratory restlessness in captive birds.
Food supply strongly influences migration: birds must leave while food is still abundant enough to build fat reserves for long flights. Some even seem to anticipate environmental changes, suggesting internal triggers.
In 1967, Russian scientists Viktor Dolnik and Tatiana Blyumental found that in chaffinches, fat birds migrate first under good conditions, while leaner ones follow latersometimes in poor weatherlikely due to social pressure from earlier departures.
Migration patterns differ widely: most species travel moderate distances, but others, like the wandering albatross, spend much of their lives in flight, covering vast distances efficiently by riding air currents.

Reggaeton, a hybrid genre blending Jamaican dancehall reggae, Latin salsa and merengue, and North American hip-hop, gained mainstream U.S. attention with Daddy Yankee's 2004 hit "Gasolina." Though rooted in Panama, Puerto Ricans refined the genre in the early 1990s, influenced by Spanish-language rap versions of Jamaican reggae and dancehall. The 1991 track "Dem Bow" by Shabba Ranks (adapted by Panamanian artist El General) established reggaeton's signature beat, which remains central to the genre.
Reggaeton spread initially in U.S. cities with strong Puerto Rican communities, aided by DJs like Playero, and has since gained international popularity with its energetic, street-inspired rhythms appealing to diverse audiences. Critics sometimes dismiss it as repetitive or violent, but artists and scholars defend its artistic significance and underground credibility. Its electronic, syncopated beats differentiate it from traditional Latin music.

Reggaeton spread initially in U.S. cities with strong Puerto Rican communities, aided by DJs like Playero, and has since gained international popularity with its energetic, street-inspired rhythms appealing to diverse audiences. Critics sometimes dismiss it as repetitive or violent, but artists and scholars defend its artistic significance and underground credibility. Its electronic, syncopated beats differentiate it from traditional Latin music.

This text discusses bird migration where birds tend to travel bewteen breeding and wintering grounds. While weather and food is available for them which is one of the most important factors for birds, birds also rely on the internal clock to time their migrations. The experiment on chaffinches revealed that the birds that are more physically fit migrate first and social pressure from these birds can influence leaner birds to migrate even under unfavorable conditions.

During the great depression, President Roosevelt created the CCC to provide jobs for young men, and improve the community around them. Congress allowed the president to manage the program himself. The men were paid a large sum of money (for the time), primarily to their families. The program grew immensely over the course of a few years, and they learned, were housed, and built to support the community.

Usually, when a star roughly the size of the sun gets old, it'll turn into a red gaint, before releasing its layers into a nebula that eventually reveals the core, now a white dwarf, which then lasts for billions of years. But some white dwarfs may instead be capable of reforming into a giant star, although for a brief amount of time, cosmically speaking, as it does not have enough resources to sustain itself, turning back into a white dwarf. FG Sagittae is an example of a similar case, as it seems to attempt to restart its fusion, but ultimately releasing black smoke that obscures its light. Gehrz and his team have been monitoring FG Sagittae and has recorded the temperature of Sagittae's surface, which is not hot enough to  properly maintain active nuclear fusion. Cosmic dust that the core produces also powers a stellar wind, and provides a glow that has lasted for the past decade, and the core has been losing mass from these winds and loss of dust over the years. It is possible that even after the core stops producing these, and turns back into a dwarf, the dust could possibly be the start of new stellar structures, but that is for future society to find out.

Migration is a common behavior for more than 50 billion birds worldwide, occuring annually, and we do not have a full understanding of why they do so. Weather is a strong factor, as the birds move towards warmer weather. However, weather is an unreliable measure, so it is thought that birds have an internal ability to know when to migrate, which can be seen in caged birds through "migratory restlessness". Food is both important towards the bird's capability of migration (having to build up body fat for energy), and a reason for the bird to migrate, in order to reach a new food supply. Ornithologists discovered that fatter chaffinces start their migration first, with leaner ones following later. There is an influence where the healthier chaffinces migrating causes the more unready chaffinces to be pressured into migrating too. The length of migration also varies, with some species taking only days or weeks, while others take months. Some birds even spend less energy in the air than sitting still, including albatrosses who spent almost their entire life in the air, with immense migrations, using the air currents to support their travelling.

Before a sunlike star faces this phenomina of "death," when it is apporaching the near ends of its life. It shall first become a red giant that grows exponentially, thus reaching a size that is a hundred times larger. Though after this process finishes, the outer layer of the star blows off and releases a gas called a planetary nebula. This gas leaves the core exposed and leads it to transform into a white dwarf--usually it'll cool off the extreme temparetures, however temperature fluctuation might occur and regnite nuclear fusion. Giving room to a flicker mechanism that brings life back once more through energy bursts.

The music genre known as "Reggaeton" was said to have originally released in Panama in the 1970s and 80s, though it wasn't until the early 1990s that the genre got perfected. Reggaeton is music inspired with a blend of Spanish rap music and dancehall reggae, thus it finallly made its grand entrance onto mainstream U.S through the radio Daddy Yankee's 2004. It was said that one of the effects that lead to the evolution of reggaeton had to do with ethnic migrations, particularly with Jamacian laborers who migrated to Panama to aid with the Panama Canal. Essentially, Panamanians become exposed to the Jamaican reggae, thus leading to  the 20th century move of the modernized, more electronic form of Jamaican dancehill regga that infiltrated Puerto Rico. Ultimately, reggaeton as a genre became offical in 1991, through the recording of spanish by a Panamanian artist.

Ultimately, reggaeton as a genre became offical in 1991, through the recording of spanish by a Panamanian artist.

The music genre known as "Reggaeton" was said to have originally released in Panama in the 1970s and 80s, though it wasn't until the early 1990s that the genre got perfected. Reggaeton is music inspired with a blend of Spanish rap music and dancehall reggae, thus it finallly made its grand entrance onto mainstream U.S through the radio Daddy Yankee's 2004. Migration is an event most commonly observed through difference species such as butterflies, birds, ducks, etc... Though this passage primarily focuses on the migration of birds and takes the natural world into account, suggesting seasonal influences (color breeding = spring and summer, warmer locations = autumn and winter). Off of birds alone, they make up for over 50 billion of species that have migration as a part of their annual cycle. Additionally, this doesn't include all birds as there particular birds who remain in a single location all year round (tropical locations). Birds determine when to migrate through a variety of complex factors, the most basic idea being the cycle of the weather (seasons, colder weathers leading to birds migrating to warmer locations). Though this isn't always the case as obstructions in the clouds could impair the ability to predict the right time to migrate, hence birds must rely on an interal clock to time the seasonal movments (migratory restlessness).

The origins of the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), began with President Roosevelet himself. When he went to Congress he sought authorization of the program, originally said to be called Civillian Corps Reforestation Youth Rehabilitation Movment (CCRYRM), though it was changed out of the length from the acronym. The influence of this program had largely to do with his fondness for tree farming, though it's also safe to say unemployment was also considered within the program to help young enlisted men in volunteer work (national forests, parks, & federal public lands). Roosevelt was passionate for reforestion, thus he discovered the opportunities to create hope for young men by not only impacting the improvment of infrastructure, education, and earnings towards their families. The CCC was widely acknowledged for its ability to draw change and heal its land, especially through a hard time in history (The Great Depression).

Charitable donations is generally acknowledged as one of the top forms of moral behavior, most notably spotted in locations such as churches with the aims to support organizations who lend a helping hand to those in poverty or unfortunate circumstances. These forms of donations are highly acknowledged from philanthropists such as Ted Stumbcher and Jacqueline Novogratz who have advocated the importance of stratigies that aim to address issues systemically; poverty and solutions that lead to long-term effects. Other philanthropists, Karen Pitts, created a win-win-win situation where the wineriers (the drinkers) are able to enjoy themselves while being directly associated with helping others through financial proceeds. As a result, modern philanthropic orgazations often use a system that allows donors to choose their donation methods (creative fundraising events, clothing recycling bins, environmental needs).

Traditionally, people think of charity as giving money to someone in need, like dropping change in a salvation army bucket, giving at church, or helping a homeless person. Most charity has come from religious groups because helping others is seen as a very moral thing to do. Churches often organize collections or soup kitchens to help the poor. But some people, like Ted Stumbacher, think charity could be more effective if it focused on long-term solutions, not just temporary help with food or shelter. Over the past 20 years charities have started to change how they work by finding creative ways to help, like clothing drop boxes that give clothes to people in need and such.

Most charity has come from religious groups because helping others is seen as a very moral thing to do. Churches often organize collections or soup kitchens to help the poor. But some people, like Ted Stumbacher, think charity could be more effective if it focused on long-term solutions, not just temporary help with food or shelter. Reggaeton hit the U.S. radio big time with Daddy Yankee's "Gasolina" song in 2004, but it had been popular in Latin America for a while already. It's a mix of Jamaican dancehall reggae, Latin music like salsa and merengue, and hip-hop/ electronic music from the U.S. It probably started in Panama, but Puerto Ricans really made it their own in the 1990s. The music grew from people moving between countries, like Jamaicans going to Panama and brining reggae with them. Later, DJs in Puerto Rico brought new dancehall sounds to the island, which influenced reggaeton even more.

One of the most successful New Deal programs came from President Roosevelt, whole loved both helping people and taking care of trees. In 1993, he created a program to put unemployed young men to work in national forests, parks, and other public lands. He first called it the Civilian Corps Reforestation Youth Rehabilitation Movement, but it was quickly shortened to the Civilian Conservation Corps, CCC. Congress approved it but let Roosevelt run it his way for 2 years. The Labor Department chose the workers, the War Department housed and fed them, and the Agriculture and Interior Department supervised the projects. The men earned $30 a month, with most of it sent to support their families.

About a billion years before a sunlike star dies, it becomes a red giant and grows huge, about a hundred times bigger than before. After this phase, the star blows off its outer layers, creating a gas cloud called a planetary nebula. The nebula expands and becomes less dense, leaving the star's core exposed. This core turns into a white dwarf, which slowly gives off its leftover heat for billions of years before fading to black. Some white dwarfs, though, don't go quietly. Their cores can suddenly heat up again to millions of degrees, causing debrief bursts of new energy and nuclear fusion, almost like the star comes back to life for a short time.

Many birds migrate every year, moving to cooler areas in the spring and summer to breed and to warmer areas in autumn and winter. Not all birds migrate though, some, especially in the tropics, stay in one place year-round. Figuring out when to start migration is complicated and depends on many factors, Weather is a big influence, since cooler temperatures and more rain push birds toward warmer areas. But weather isn't always predictable, and things like clouds can hide the sun or stars that birds use for navigation. Because of this, birds also rely on an internal clock. Scientists have even noticed migratory restlessness in birds kept in cages at the same time wild birds start their migrations

The passage from the article discusses the different stages a star goes through after it "dies". First becoming a red giant, increasing immensely in diameter, until the start of the next stellar phase in becoming a planetary nebula. Also mentioning, the theory of stellar evolution, the says the temperature in the stellar core can fluctuate to the point that the core can ever start back up to a giant star generating new energy. The passage brings up a research team led by Robert A. Gehrz that has examined what has been going on near the star FG Sagittae surface which seems to be in this step of the stellar evolution.

The passage from the article discusses the music genre of Reggaeton. Starting off with the history/evolution of the genre. Reggaeton was thought to have been originated in Panama, however the cultivation and popularity of its style took place within Puerto Rico. The genre was made concrete with the 1991 single by Shabba Ranks, "Dem Bow" that was recorded in Spanish by artist El General as "Son Bow". This track has been a continued influence on the underlying rhythm of almost every reggaeton song, even now. The article also notes that the genre hasn't always been taken seriously. As musicologist Ethan Perry dismisses the genre by saying that the genre's lack of imagination will be its downfall. The overall topic discussed in the article is migratory birds. Starting off with the weather being how birds know when to start migrating to warmer climates. Another possible reasoning is that birds have an internal clock that tells them when they should leave. Also bringing up the fact that caged birds have been noticed to act up during such periods. The articles then goes on to discuss that for most migratory birds, food supply is a major factor for the need to move locations. Noting, a 1967 study done by Russian ornithologists Viktor Dolnik and Tatiana Blyumental who collected chaffinches as they migrated along the Baltic coast. The scientists determined the social influence that fat, healthy birds have on the remaining population. Observing that these birds left at different times depending how healthy they were; with fatter birds initializing the migration. The article notes that although this pattern can be seen it might not be the case for other species of migratory birds.

The passage of the article discusses human nature when it comes to charitable giving. Starting off by listing a few examples of what people think of charitable giving, such as dropping change into the salvation army basket. Going to say how Ted Stumbacher, believes that truly effective philanthropy is rooted in an economic mindset. Feeling that religious organizations often provide only a temporary reprieve from suffering. Other philanthropist, like Karen Pitts seek to engage doners by combining donations with activities creating a win-win scenario. The article ends by noting that such innovative philanthropic ideas only work on a small scale.

Reggaeton's modern musical style originated from Jamaican reggae, and was eventually assimilated by Panamanians via the construction of the Panama Canal throught the 20th century. Shabba Ranks's 1991 "Dem Bow" ultimately solidified the genre, especially following the Spanish re-record by El General that overarchingly influences the entire genre today.

A star generates energy through nuclear fusion. Around a billion years before it dies, the star becomes an inflated red giant, before exploding into a planetary nebula, which will eventually become less dense to reveal the white dwarf within, a weaker, less impressive reminder of what the star once was. White dwarves can, however, undergo periodic flares of nuclear fusion, becoming short-lived, temporary giant stars that in their process of energy generation jut out "dust clouds" of carbon atoms. Such is the case with FG Sagittae, examined by astronomers through infrared light tracking, where they discovered it having a temperature being around 650C and generating winds that carry substantial masses of stellar material away from FG Saggitae per year. This fanned-out material ultimately gives rise to astronomical structures surrounding the dwarf, including planets, moons, asteroids, and even life.

Such is the case with FG Sagittae, examined by astronomers through infrared light tracking, where they discovered it having a temperature being around 650C and generating winds that carry substantial masses of stellar material away from FG Saggitae per year. This fanned-out material ultimately gives rise to astronomical structures surrounding the dwarf, including planets, moons, asteroids, and even life.

The New Deal established the Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC), partly out of Franklin Roosevelt's love for trees himself. Lasting two years, the work was almost entirely divided within the executive branch of government through executive orders. The CCC official began on April 5, 1933. Its earliest enrollees were veterans who'd set up camp demanding bonuses for their services in the war. Roosevelt, unrelenting, provided them with shelter and necessities, and his wife to soothe the camp, which eventually convinced about 2500 of those men to join the CCC. The CCC ended in 1942, resulting in new fire towers, telephone lines, improved transportation infrastructure, rejuvenated forests, amongst other great contributions. Beyond that, it also granted literacy and hope to over a hundred thousand Americans.

FG Sagittae is a star that is dying, with every years having a lower temperature and sometimes shining brightly. A research team lead by Robert A. Gehrz, University of Minnesota, studied the infrared properties of this star. They concluded that the dying star is creating clouds of gas that carry rich carbon atoms which can form new asteroids, moons, etc. in the future.

It is very common for birds to make seasonal trips. Birds tend to migrate only when their food reserves are high but due to the unpredictability of the seasonal weather, birds relay on an internal clock to time their seasonal movements and to help accommodate variations in weather and food supply. A researcher, Viktor Dolnik, 1967, found that "fat" chaffinches birds were always they first to begin the migration period early in the morning as they had more energy to begin the trip. As the day progressed, "leaner" birds would begin their migration although their energy reverse weren't full, haven't ate enough or weren't "fat" enough. This was thought to occur due to pressure of being left behind. These patterns are not true for every species of birds as some can travel greater distances using little energy and vice-versa.

President Roosevelt created and structured a program known as Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) in 1933 that was designed to get healthy young men from ages 17 - 27 to work in regional and nations forests. Veterans wanted compensation for being part of the war, but due to the economic grounds, FDR was unable to provide this so instead he changed the age restrictions to the CCC program and provided everyone who joined with tents, showers, mess halls, etc. By 1934 the program had expand exponentially and the development and improvements made to the national parks was incredible. As much as the men in this program helped the communality it also helped them by teaching them how to read, write, work hard and give them a dose of self esteem they never had before.

Reggaeton is a music sensation that main it to mainstream U.S. radio in 2004 with Daddy Yankee's hit song "Gasolina." Before it became famous it went through musical evolution in which it was created with combinations of Jamaican reggae, Latin American salsa, merengue, and north American hip-hop. Although some critic the music genre as predicable, violet and sexually suggestive, reggaeton is a distinct art form that achieved global prevalence.
